Day 66: Bridging the Gap (CORS)

**Topics Covered:**
1. What is CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)?
2. Why Browsers block requests from different ports (Security).
3. Allowing origins using `@CrossOrigin`.
4. Global CORS Configuration.

**Learning Summary:**
Today I faced a common error: "Access to fetch at... blocked by CORS policy." This happens because my Frontend runs on Port 5500 (Live Server) and Backend on Port 8080. Browsers treat them as different "Origins" and block communication for safety. I learned how to whitelist my frontend URL in Spring Boot to allow data exchange.

**Code Snippet:**
```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/users")
// Allow requests specifically from my Frontend Port
@CrossOrigin(origins = "[http://127.0.0.1:5500](http://127.0.0.1:5500)") 
public class UserController {

    @GetMapping
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userService.findAll();
    }
}
Global Config (Better Way):

Java

@Configuration
public class WebConfig implements WebMvcConfigurer {
    @Override
    public void addCorsMappings(CorsRegistry registry) {
        registry.addMapping("/**").allowedOrigins("[http://127.0.0.1:5500](http://127.0.0.1:5500)");
    }
}
